body_text.text:
On Labour Day May 1, 2003, The Beijing Times published a poster titled Declare War on SARS! (figure 1
). The five-character phrase grammatically recalls the five-character slogan of the Communist Revolution “Serve the People!”. A young man dressed in proletariat blue raises his right fist and breaks through the top border calling the masses to unite behind the government to conquer SARS. His posture mirrors that of a young barefoot doctor in a 1970 public-health poster for the prevention of respiratory tract infections (figure 2
). The red cross has moved from the barefoot doctor's first-aid satchel to a surgical cap replacing the old red star on Maoist military caps. A white face mask, which became the international symbol of the SARS epidemic, now covers his mouth.
